Youtao Lu

About

Youtao Lu is currently a Ph.D. candidate of the Department of Cognitive, Linguistic and Psychological Sciences (CLPS) at Brown University. He is interested in how spoken language are processed by adults and learnt by young kids, and how these differ across languages. His current project investigates the processing of homophones (words that are pronounced the same but mean different things, like “knight” and “night”) within and without contexts in English, Mandarin and Japanese.

Education

Brown University | Providence, RI

Ph.D. in Cognitive Science | September 2016 - May 2022 (Expected)

Tsinghua University | Beijing, CHINA

B.A. in English Language and Literature | September 2012 - June 2016

B.A. in Economics | September 2012 - June 2016

Experience

21st Century English Education Media (CHINA) | Editor Intern | July 2011
